**Step 2 – Apply the linear trend**

1. **Rate of change**  
   \[
   \text{Rate}=\frac{2^\circ\text{C}-5^\circ\text{C}}{58\text{ days}}
   =\frac{-3^\circ\text{C}}{58\text{ days}}
   \approx -0.052\,^\circ\text{C per day}
   \]

2. **Days from December 3 to December 25**  
   \[
   25-3 = 22\text{ days}
   \]

3. **Temperature change over those 22 days**  
   \[
   \Delta T = 22 \times (-0.052^\circ\text{C}) \approx -1.144^\circ\text{C}
   \]

4. **Estimated low on December 25**  
   \[
   T_{\text{Dec 25}} = 5^\circ\text{C} + \Delta T
   = 5^\circ\text{C} - 1.144^\circ\text{C}
   \approx 3.86^\circ\text{C}
   \]

So, using the linear trend inferred from the two given dates, the low temperature on **December 25** would be approximately **\(3.9^\circ\text{C}\)**.

